      "description": "Web-Based Game Asset Editor\n\nImplement a browser-based visual editor that allows developers or designers to create, view, modify, and manage all core game asset types, including ships, local space environments, ship subsystems, weapon stats, and hardpoints, without requiring direct file or code manipulation.\n\nRequirements:\n\nAsset Type Coverage:\n- Ships: Create and edit ship definitions including name, class, faction, hull stats, mass, dimensions, and any classification metadata\n- Local Space Environments: Define and edit spatial regions including navigation hazards, gravitational bodies, spawn zones, and environmental properties\n- Ship Subsystems: Configure individual subsystem definitions including type, health thresholds, power draw, damage cascade linkages, and performance characteristics\n- Weapon Stats: Edit weapon definitions including damage, fire rate, range, projectile velocity, heat generation, ammo type references, and accuracy profiles\n- Hardpoints: Define and assign hardpoint positions on a ship, including mount type, facing arc, compatible weapon classes, and location relative to ship geometry\n\nEditor Functionality:\n- Asset browser with filterable, searchable list views for each asset category\n- Detail editor panel with clearly labeled fields and input validation for each asset type\n- Create new assets from scratch or by duplicating an existing asset as a template\n- Save changes persistently to the backing data store or config files used by the game engine\n- Delete assets with a confirmation prompt and dependency warning if the asset is referenced elsewhere\n- Unsaved change indicators and a discard or cancel flow to prevent accidental data loss\n\nHardpoint Visualizer:\n- Display a top-down or isometric schematic of the ship hull\n- Allow hardpoints to be positioned visually on the schematic with drag-and-drop or coordinate input\n- Show firing arc overlays per hardpoint\n- Highlight conflicts such as overlapping arcs or incompatible mount assignments\n\nData Integrity:\n- Validate that referenced assets exist (e.g., a hardpoint's assigned weapon class must exist in the weapon definitions)\n- Warn on save if any required fields are empty or out of valid range\n- Preserve data format compatibility with the existing asset schema used by the simulation engine\n\nIntegration:\n- Read from and write to the same asset definition files or database consumed by the game backend, ensuring no duplication or format divergence\n- Coexist cleanly with the existing web GUI panels (Helm, Tactical, Subsystem Status) without routing or state conflicts",
